1. Introduction¶

In this tutorial, we are going to be exploring the Data Science pipeline when it comes to data curation, parsing, data analysis and visualization, and machine learning. Throughout this tutorial, we are going to be analyzing COVID-19 cases in the United States and their relationship between the number of cases with race, sex, age groups, and ethnicity. We will also be looking at general trends in the number of COVID-19 cases throughout the United States broken down nationally, by states, and by counties. All of the data used in this tutorial is within the time frame of the beginning of 2020 until April 2021.

1.1: COVID-19 Background Information¶

COVID-19 is the disease caused by SARS-CoV-2, the coronavirus emerged in December of 2019. Cases of COVID-19 can be severe, and has caused millions of deaths around the worlds as well as lasting health problems in individuals who have survived the illness. Coronavirus can be transmitted from person to person, and can only be diagnosed with a laboratory test. Prevention measures such as physical distancing, mask wearing, hand hygiene and staying away from others were hugely important at the beginning of the pandemic. However, as we are currently more than a year into the pandemic, COVID-19 vaccines have be authoized for emergency use the U.S. Food and Drug Adminstration, and vaccination programs continue to be in full effect across the country and in many parts of the world.

As of May 15th, the total worldwide case amount is 162 million cases with 3.36 million deaths worldwide. In the United States, as of May 15th we have a total of 33.9 million cases with 585 thousand deaths. The huge amount of cases in the United States has left us wanting to examine the relationship between the number of COVID-19 cases in the United States and race, sex, age group, ethnicity, and deaths.

1.2: Libraries Used¶

  • Pandas: this library is used to display and organize the data into data frames
  • Numpy: this library is used to support our data when using Pandas
  • Requests: this library is used to do HTTP requests through Python
  • Matplotlib: this library is used to be able to visualized our data through graphs
  • Seaborn: used for data visualization that is based on Matplotlib
  • US: used to work with US and US State metadata
  • Statsmodels: used to work with linear regression

2. Data Collection¶

There are plenty of datasets that could be found online that we could of used for COVID-19 data within the United States. We settled on using data directly from the New York Times and the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention.

2.1: Information about data sources¶

Throughout this project, there will be a total of 4 datasets being used.

The first dataset was found from the Centers for Disease Control and Prevention:

  • The CDC's public use dataset has 19 elements for all COVID-19 cases shared with the CDC and includes demographics, geography and exporsure history just to name a few fields. For our purposes will only focus on the sex, race, age group, and ethnicity fields of this particular dataset.Lastly, it is important to state that the last data points are dated from April, 2021.

The following 3 datasets were found from The New York Times github page:

  • The New York Times released primary data that kept track of the daily cumulative number of cases and deaths reported in each county and state across the United States since the beginning of the pandemic. Since these datasets were stored in the NYT github account the following lines of code was used to create a file with the data. Lastly, it is important to state that the last data points are dated from May 11, 2021.

    • Dataset Fields:
      • Date: the date the cases were reported
      • County: only applicable to the dataset with counties, but lists the county name
      • State: only applicable to the dataset with states, but lists the state name
      • Fips: code which uniquely identify geographic areas
      • Cases: cumulative number of cases
      • Deaths: cumulative number of deaths
    • National US Data:

2.3: Data cleanup¶

Since the New York Times datasets contain cumulative amount of cases and deaths, it can become difficult to create visuals for our data if we wanted to see how many new cases or new deaths were added for each row. Below, we will add two new columns into our dataframes that will contain information regarding new cases and new deaths.

Similarly, with your demographics_us_data DataFrame we only want to keep track of race, sex, age group and ethnicity columns so any other columns we will drop from our DataFrame

In [13]:
# since case numbers and deaths numbers are cumulative, these following lines will find the differences between the rows
# to get an accurate value of how many new cases/deaths were added per row
us_states = us_states.sort_values(by=['state', 'date'])
us_states['new_cases'] = us_states.groupby(['state'])['cases'].diff().fillna(0)
us_states['new_deaths'] = us_states.groupby(['state'])['deaths'].diff().fillna(0)

us_counties = us_counties.sort_values(by=['state','county','date'])
us_counties['new_cases'] = us_counties.groupby(['state','county'])['cases'].diff().fillna(0)
us_counties['new_deaths'] = us_counties.groupby(['state'])['deaths'].diff().fillna(0)

us_data = us_data.sort_values(by=['date'])
us_data['new_cases'] = us_data['cases'].diff().fillna(0)
us_data['new_deaths'] = us_data['deaths'].diff().fillna(0)

3. Data Analysis and Visualization¶

Now that we have our data, we can begin to visualize our data by processing it to compare it with other columns in our Data Frame. Using libraries like Matplotlib and Seaborn, we are able to create graphs and plots to visualize our data.

3.1: COVID-19 Cases trends in the United States¶

Before we take a deep dive into seeing the relationship between the number of COVID-19 cases and race, ethnicity, age group, sex. We will take a look at the general trends of COVID-19 cases in the country as well as well per state. By looking at these trends, we can understand how the our other data points might be affect because of the general decrease in cases as vaccine distribution has began on a mass scale.

In [15]:
# using pandas built in plot function we are able to create a line graph to show the number of cases over time
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(15,9))
us_data.plot(x='date',y='new_cases', ax = ax)
plt.ticklabel_format(style='plain', axis='y')
ax.set_title("Growth of COVID-19 Cases in the United States")
ax.set_ylabel("Number of Cases")
ax.set_xlabel("Date")
plt.show()

Number of Cases over time in the United States¶

Our line graph displays the general trend of COVID-19 cases in the United States over time. From a first glance, we can notice when COVID-19 began to spread throughout the US starting in mid Janurary of 2020. As more cases were added we can say that rates of transmission between the population also began to increase which also led to cases increasing into March 2020. Towards the end of March is when we saw most states releasing lockdown mandates, these restriction continued throughout the summer of 2020. As the Fall and Winter seasons approached, we began to see a huge spike in new case numbers because people were gathered more inside than they were during the summer time.

Number of Cases per State and Territory¶

Once we broke down the distribution of Covid-19 cases across the United States and ordered them by total cases depending on the states, we are able to see which states contain high amounts of cases. Amongst those states, California had the most, followed by Texas, then by New York, and then Florida. This data does not surprise us due to the knowledge that these four states have the highest population in the United States. But also based on that knowledge, we see that Pennsylvania is also a top 5 populous state but has half the amount of cases than New York. Following the analysis previously, we see that Puerto Rico has a much higher count of Covid-19 cases, which also definitely has correlation to it's higher population count compared to the Virgin Islands, Guam, and Northern Mariana Islands.

4. Machine Learning¶

In the previous section, we were able to visualize the data to get a better understanding of how the number of COVID-19 cases related to age group, race, sex, and ethnicity. While our main dataset that contains demographic fields does not maintain a case count it is hard to create a datamodel surrounding that data. That is why we will continue to use the datasets from the New York Times as their datasets provide case counts.

4.1: Linear Regression Models¶

Using our us_data DataFrame, we will try to find a linear relationship between the number of new deaths and the number of new cases in our dataset.

In [42]:
# we are able to build our model using the statsmodel library 
# we define our variables 
# we print out our model
X = us_data['new_cases']
Y = us_data['new_deaths']
X = sm.add_constant(X)
md = sm.OLS(Y,X).fit()
print(md.summary())

4.2: Hypothesis testing and understanding the results¶

Before we can analyze our results we first have to set forth our null and alternative hypothesis.

  • Null Hypothesis: There is no relationship between the number of new deaths and new cases
  • Alternative Hypothesis: There is a relationship between the number of new deaths and new cases

Looking at our model summary, we can see that we have a value of 0.00 for P>|t| which is less than 0.05 meaning that it is quite significant meaning that we can reject our null hypothesis. By rejecting our null hypothesis, we can say that there is a relationship between the number of new deaths and new cases.

When also looking our model, when looking at our R-squared value will allow us to measure how well the regression line fits with the real data points. Essentially, the higher the value the better the fit for our data points. The value for R-squared is listed as 0.483, from that we can conclude that to an extent our regression line does fit some of our real data points.

Lastly, our model gives us a coefficient value. When looking at this value, if we encounter a positive value means that the two variables in this case new deaths and new cases are directly proportional. This means that where an increase in one quantity causes a corresponding increase in the other quantity.

When looking at our graph that plot our regression line, we can conclude that most of our early data points reside closer to our regression line. As the number of cases increased than we saw our data points reside much further away from our regression line.
